# Prefer early returns (guard clauses)

- Use **guard clauses** to handle invalid inputs and edge cases first.
- Avoid deep nesting (multiple `if`/`else` blocks).
- Keep the “happy path” left-aligned and easy to scan.

## Examples

### Conditionals

```ts
// ❌ Avoid
function parsePort(input?: string) {
  if (input) {
    const port = Number(input);
    if (Number.isInteger(port) && port >= 1 && port <= 65535) {
      return port;
    }
  }
  return 19132;
}

// ✅ Prefer
function parsePort(input?: string) {
  if (!input) return 19132;

  const port = Number(input);
  if (!Number.isInteger(port)) return 19132;
  if (port < 1 || port > 65535) return 19132;

  return port;
}
```

### Error handling

```ts
// ✅ Prefer: validate early, return early
if (!hostname) {
  return reply.status(400).send({ error: "VALIDATION_ERROR", message: "hostname is required" });
}
```
